ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 5
 shows that there are three major absorption peaks, designated S1, S2, and S3, respectively, which increase in intensity in the Ir(III) complex–GQD nanocomposites. The electron-donating substituent shifts these absorption peaks to longer wavelength region, improving the efficiency of charge collection, while the electron-attracting substituent, especially the strongly electron-attracting substituent, leads to a reduction in the absorption intensities. To understand the nature of these absorption peaks, the absorption spectra of the isolated GQD and Ir(III) complex extracted directly from the nanocomposite without further optimization of their structures are calculated. In addition, the electron and hole densities corresponding to these absorption peaks are determined by natural transition orbital (NTO) analysis. The S1 and S2 states are composite states containing optical transitions from both the GQD and Ir(III) complexes, while the S3 state is mainly from the GQD. NTO analysis reveals that the three main absorption peaks in the pristine Ir(III) complex–GQD nanocomposite (Supplemental tables S2 and Table 2
) are determined by the π,π* transition originating from either the GQD or the ppy ligand. Notably, S1 includes components of ligand-to-ligand charge transfer (1LLCT), intraligand charge transfer (1ILCT), and metal-to-ligand charge transfer (1MLCT) in the Ir(III) complex, while S2 and S3 are dictated by the π,π* transition in the GQD. In the Ir(III) complex–GQD nanocomposite with electron-donating substituents (D4 and D5), S1 and S2 are determined mainly by the 1ILCT in the ppy [54], while S3 is mainly dictated by the π,π* transition in the GQD. For the Ir(III) complex–GQD nanocomposite with electron-withdrawing substituents (W2, W3, and W6), S1 and S2 are a combination of 1LLCT, 1MLCT, and π,π* transition in the GQD, while S3 is mainly determined by the π,π* transition in the GQD. Furthermore, the orbital contributions to the S1, S2, and S3 states in the Ir(III) complex–GQD nanocomposites vary depending on the 2-aryl substituent, resulting in different oscillator strengths due to the different electron-donating and -attracting groups. It should be noted that the polar solvent does not cause any shift in the absorption maxima, only a change in their intensities (Supplemental Fig. S1).
